Install `jazz-napi` directly and create one server-only context for the process:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH! },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Reuse this context across requests; do not initialize the native runtime per request. Use a stable, backed-up `dataPath`, explicitly await the required write tier, and call `await jazz.shutdown()` on process termination. A memory driver is ephemeral and requires an upstream `serverUrl`. Server-connected backend/scoped handles require `BACKEND_SECRET`; local-only unscoped `db()` does not. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` exclusively in server-side environment variables and out of browser bundles and logs.

Pass an accessor so changing inputs rebuilds the query.

Svelte:
```ts
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId })
);
```

Solid:
```ts
const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current input instead of tracking later changes.

Use the conventional helper-compatible tables exactly:
```ts
const app = s.schema({
  file_parts: s.table({ data: s.bytes() }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
});
```
Give each user CRUD access to their own `uploads` rows. Allow narrowly reviewed direct inserts into `files` and `file_parts`, because helpers create them before the referencing upload exists. Inherit file read/delete through `uploads.fileId`, and part read/delete through `files.partIds`:
```ts
policy.uploads.allowRead.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowInsert.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowUpdate.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowDelete.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.files.allowInsert.where({});
policy.file_parts.allowInsert.where({});
policy.files.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
policy.files.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
policy.file_parts.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
policy.file_parts.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
```
Do not grant broad reads or updates. If arbitrary client chunk creation is unacceptable, perform uploads through a trusted backend.

Require edge settlement for both the chunked file and its owning row:
```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label,
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
Only report success after both awaits complete. For download, request the edge tier so missing local chunks can be fetched:
```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return blob;
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // File row is not visible: show unavailable/not-authorized state.
  } else if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // Distinguish invalid-file-record, missing-part, and part-size-mismatch.
    // Show incomplete/corrupt upload state; a stronger tier cannot repair bad upstream data.
  } else throw error;
}
```
A local incomplete state is not download success; wait for edge and still surface genuine missing or wrong-sized parts.

Keep the parent relationship alive while inherited delete permissions are evaluated. Load the upload and file, delete every referenced part, then the file, and only then the upload:
```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}
db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```
Await the relevant write tier if deletion completion must be durable before confirming success. Never delete the upload first: doing so removes the referencing path that authorizes deletion of the file and its parts.

Render from a subscription with `localUpdates: "immediate"` and `propagation: "full"`, so edits appear as soon as they are written locally. Track each returned write handle separately:

```ts
const write = db.update(app.documents, id, patch);
setStatus("pending");
void write.wait({ tier: "edge" }).then(
  () => setStatus("confirmed"),
  error => setStatus("rejected", error),
);
```

While disconnected, keep showing the optimistic value and an offline/pending indicator; the edge wait should remain pending. After `db.reconnect()`, confirmation means the nearest sync server accepted the write. On rejection, expect Jazz to remove the rejected optimistic history and show the rebuilt value plus a retry/error action. Register `db.onMutationError(...)` for un-awaited or restart-surviving failures, and dispose it with the UI owner.
